## Executive Summary

The Government of Italy is a steadily growing humanitarian donor, with
annual funding averaging around \$6.8 million and increasing
geographical reach from 8 to 16 countries between 2022 and 2025. Italy’s
funding is strategically concentrated in select regions, notably Western
Europe, with flexible earmarking at about 16%, allowing for adaptable
programming. While Italy’s transaction values are smaller and less
frequent than other top donors, this presents an opportunity to advocate
for more regular and scaled contributions. Understanding Italy’s
evolving regional focus and openness to multi-country support can guide
tailored proposal development to align with its funding priorities and
leverage its increasing role in humanitarian aid.

## Volatility

This visualization tracks the funding volatility from the Italian
government with 114 transactions recorded from June 2023 to November
2025. The average transaction value is approximately 1.0 million USD,
spread across an average of 38 transactions annually. When benchmarked
against the top 10 other donors, Italy’s average transaction amount is
significantly lower, with others averaging 2.9 million USD per
transaction and 371.3 transactions per year. The data points and trend

with some peaks reaching nearly 5 million USD but generally exhibiting
lower and less frequent funding compared to leading donors. This pattern
suggests Italy provides smaller, less consistent financial
contributions, potentially limiting project scale and predictability in
humanitarian programming. For proposal writers, these insights indicate
